The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Reliance net jumps 32% 
                                                                                                                           6                                                                                      Reliance net jumps 32% 
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                                            
	Mumbai, July 27: Reliance Industries  the countrys largest private company  today announced a 32.3 per cent surge in net profits at Rs 4,851 crore in the first quarter ended June 30 on the back of higher gas output from its fields in the Krishna-Godavari basin and improved refining margins.        
	It had notched up a net profit of Rs 3,666 crore in the same period a year ago.        
	The Mukesh Ambani flagship  which made a foray into the telecom sector after scrapping a mutually-restrictive non-compete policy with Anil Ambanis ADAG group in May  said it had ratcheted up margins across all its business segments during the quarter.        
	Turnover leapt 88 per cent to Rs 61,007 crore, easily beating the Streets estimates. Gross refining margins perked up to $7.3 a barrel against $6.8 a year ago, but was down from the $7.7 per barrel in the January-March quarter. Analysts had forecast a slightly higher refining margin of $7.7 a barrel. The refining business clocked revenues of Rs 50,531 crore, an increase of 106.8 per cent over the year-ago level of Rs 24,434 crore.         
	Production from the KG-D6 basin was 304,349 tonnes of crude oil and 5,376 million metric standard cubic metres of gas  a growth of 207 per cent and 210 per cent, respectively. Reliance said it had signed gas supply pacts with 55 customers in the fertiliser, power, city gas distribution, steel, LPG, refinery and petrochemical sectors.        
	We had another record quarter because of high operating rates and improving margins across all our businesses, RIL chairman Mukesh Ambani said.        
	The company sits on a growing mountain of cash. It reported cash and cash equivalents of Rs 26,407 crore  an accretion of Rs 4,533 crore in just three months. The cash mountain swelled 20.7 per cent over the Rs 21,874 crore it reported at the end of March 31.         
	Ahead of the earnings announcement, the Reliance stock closed at Rs 1,053.50 on the Bombay Stock Exchange, a gain of Rs 1.45, or 0.14 per cent.                                                                                                                                       
